Details:
The EN plated Bolt Carrier Group enhances reliability, lessens cleaning time,
improves corrosion resistance and minimizes required bolt lubrication.

- EN plated bolt carrier, heat treated & hardened.
- Hardened gas key, grade 8 hardened fasteners, type III sealing
compound, black phosphate outer finish and inner chrome lined.
- Black phosphate HPT/MPI bolt and extractor with Mil-Spec gas rings.

Cleaning is minimal, usually requiring only a soft cloth. Permits firing for 
longer periods of time between cleaning, as dirt and powder residue has 
no wet or oily surface to cling to.
EN provides a high lubricity and low friction co-efficient,
greatly increasing the life expectancy of a firearm due to reduced friction wear. 

Electroless nickel plating is an auto-catalytic reaction used to deposit a coating of nickel on a
substrate.  Unlike electroplating, it is not necessary to pass an electric
current through the solution to form a deposit.  This plating technique
is to prevent corrosion and wear.
EN electroless nickel plating has several advantages versus
electroplating, it provides an even deposit regardless of workpiece
geometry, and with the proper per-plate catalyst, can deposit on non-
conductive surfaces.

title: For Sale:  High Grade Belgium Browning BAR High Power Auto Rifle in 7mm Remington Mag.
postcontent:
I have this really nice Browning gas operated BAR made in Belgium.  It comes with Browning Quick Release Scope Rings & mounts.  Has a hooded front sight and flip-up rear leaf.  The see-through rings allow the the sights to be used with rings installed.

I believe this is a first-year production of the Browning BAR High Power Rifle.  The serial number is 36XXX   M8, which I think translates to a 5-digit serial number, M= High Power BAR and 8 signifies 1968, the first year of production.  I could be wrong about all of this, but this is what it looks like on the Browning websites.

It's really a pleasure to  shoot.  The action of the BAR absorbs most of the recoil, making it kick more like a .243.

The rifle is very accurate.  It retains probably 95% of bluing or better, and only a few light nicks in the stock.  It looks very nice in person.  The receiver has engraving as seen in the pictures.  

I'm told that some of the Belgium Brownings had salt-cured wood stocks, which caused rust/corrosion to the metal parts.  This rifle does NOT have a salt-cured stock, and there is NO rust or corrosion of any kind, even under the stocks.  I can e-mail pictures of various parts if you are interested.  Under the fore stock, the gas mechanism looks to be in perfect condition.  Let me make this clear, there is NO rust, nor has there ever been any rust anywhere on this rifle.  It has been on some hunts, and there is some slight wear of the bluing (hence the 95% and not 100%) but it was NEVER put away dirty and never allowed to corrode.  The bore looks great as well.

 I would like to see a CWP or such, and a FTF transaction only; I am not willing to ship.

Please include a contact phone number to rull out the scammers.  E-mails without a working phone number will be deleted.  So will e-mails asking simply if I still have it.  If this listing is still active, then I still have it.

I'm not really interested in any trades, although I might be talked into a Wilson Combat or Kimber 1911.  Not really interested in anything else.  The price is firm.  Thanks for looking!

Hey Gentleman!  Are you looking for a gun that can shoot the wings off a fly at 800 yards? Yeah?!?! Well this is not it, but if your looking for a badass thunder stick  that can knock down an elk at a reasonable range then your in the right place.  This well crafted weapon packs a kick that would make Chuck Norris cringe and the angels cry.  Sure its not the Bone Collector with all its bells and whistles but last time I checked I was a man, a man who needed nothing more then a gun that could send a projectile 2,300 fps towards an unsuspecting critter that I nicknamed supper.  "But it doesn't come in camo" you say in a whining disappointed voice.  Well if you need camo covering every square inch of gun to keep from getting spotted then this gun is not for you.  Matter of fact here are some other signs this gun may NOT be for you.
1. You brake for squirrels
2. Put the twist tie back on the bread when your done
3. Have ever heard a One Direction song and exclaimed "not bad"
4. You skipped out on poker night to watch Glee
5. You eat hot wings with a fork.
IF none of those apply to you then your a decent American and I don't mind handing this septar of a rifle over to you.  Gun shoots like a dream and at the mere age of 1 harvested her first 6x6 elk.  I'm no good with math but a friend tells me that 1 for 1 is 100% or something like that.  Gun is in near perfect condition so instead of showing you pictures of it ill show you pictures of what it can do jack.  I mean really would you rather see a Ferrari parked next to the track or see what it could do in a quarter mile.  That's what I thought.  Can't imagine you'd have any more questions but if you do or are just lookin for someone to have a beer with feel free to email me.
